      <span class="page-kicker">Case Study · 2022 · Procurement &amp; Oversight</span>
      <h1>Municipal Software Replacement — Four Years to Get There</h1>
      <p class="page-hero__lead">
        Nipissing Township approved a major software change in 2022. Years later, the original path had failed,
        the scope had drifted, and the Township only got to a working result after switching vendors and effectively starting over.
      </p>
    </div>
    <aside class="page-hero__aside">
      <h2>Why it matters</h2>
      <div class="page-hero__chips">
        <span class="page-hero__chip">Flawed procurement</span>
        <span class="page-hero__chip">Scope drift</span>
        <span class="page-hero__chip">Late reset</span>
        <span class="page-hero__chip">Weak oversight</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        A working outcome does not erase a weak process. Residents should be able to see what was approved,
        what changed, when it failed, and who pushed for a reset.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </div>
