<section class="about-overlap" aria-label="Case study summary">
  <div class="about-overlap__inner">
    <div class="about-stat">
      <strong>What changed</strong>
      <span>The Township did not simply choose one proposal. The process moved from an RFP to a different hybrid solution, then later to a vendor reset.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="about-stat">
      <strong>What concerns me</strong>
      <span>The original procurement path was declared inadequate, but the process did not visibly restart when the scope changed.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="about-stat">
      <strong>What this shows</strong>
      <span>Major technology projects need clearer procurement discipline, milestone reporting, and visible course correction.</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <span class="section__eyebrow">Overview</span>
    <h2 class="section__title">A project that drifted instead of being reset.</h2>
    <p class="section__lead" style="max-width:60ch;">
      In 2022, Nipissing Township set out to modernize its municipal software. The goal made sense.
      The process did not. The RFP did not produce a clean result, the solution changed, the project drifted for years,
      and the Township only arrived at a working outcome after changing direction.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--warm">
  <div class="container">
    <span class="section__eyebrow">How the file moved</span>
    <h2 class="section__title">One procurement. Several different realities.</h2>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-item__year">2022</div>
        <div class="timeline-item__body">
          <h3>An RFP was issued</h3>
          <p>Two submissions were received: MuniSoft at roughly $45,741 and TownSuite at roughly $411,150.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-item__year">2022</div>
        <div class="timeline-item__body">
          <h3>The RFP was called inadequate</h3>
          <p>Instead of restarting the process, the Township moved toward a different hybrid software solution.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-item__year">2022–2025</div>
        <div class="timeline-item__body">
          <h3>The project drifted</h3>
          <p>Implementation did not land cleanly, timelines stretched, funds carried forward, and there was no obvious public reset point.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-item__year">2025</div>
        <div class="timeline-item__body">
          <h3>The vendor path changed</h3>
          <p>Council acknowledged TownSuite had not successfully converted for Township needs. The agreement was terminated and MuniSoft was approved.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--navy">
  <div class="container">
    <span class="section__eyebrow section__eyebrow--light">What doesn’t add up</span>
    <h2 class="section__title section__title--light">The process never really reset when it should have.</h2>
    <div class="value-grid">
      <article class="value-card">
        <span>Issue 01</span>
        <h3>The RFP was declared inadequate — but the process kept going</h3>
        <p>If the Township could not rely on the RFP to determine the required system, that should have triggered a formal restart.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="value-card">
        <span>Issue 02</span>
        <h3>The final path did not match the original competition</h3>
        <p>The Township did not simply choose one of the two proposals. The solution changed, but the procurement path was not clearly reopened.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="value-card">
        <span>Issue 03</span>
        <h3>Years passed without visible Council intervention</h3>
        <p>What is hard to see in the public record is the moment Council clearly said: this is not working, and we need a different path.</p>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div class="callout-banner" style="margin-top:1.5rem;">
      <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem; line-height:1.2;">A good ending does not fix a weak middle.</h3>
      <p>The Township may now have a functioning system. The question is how much drift, delay, and unclear decision-making happened before it got there.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <span class="section__eyebrow">The real issue</span>
    <h2 class="section__title">What did the Township actually buy — and when did Council know the path had failed?</h2>
    <p class="section__lead" style="max-width:60ch;">
      Municipal software is rarely one product. It is modules, add-ons, integrations, implementation work, and support.
      When a project of this size changes shape repeatedly, residents should be able to see what was originally contemplated,
      what changed, why it changed, and when Council concluded the earlier route was no longer good enough.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      That is not just a technology question. It is an accountability question.
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--warm">
  <div class="container">
    <span class="section__eyebrow">What I’d do differently</span>
    <h2 class="section__title">What better oversight would look like</h2>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-item__year">A</div>
        <div class="timeline-item__body">
          <h3>Restart a flawed procurement process</h3>
          <p>If the RFP no longer reflects the actual solution being pursued, Council should stop and restart instead of letting a major project drift into a different scope.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-item__year">B</div>
        <div class="timeline-item__body">
          <h3>Require milestone reporting</h3>
          <p>Council should receive recurring public checkpoints on major implementations, with a clear expectation that failed paths come back for review.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-item__year">C</div>
        <div class="timeline-item__body">
          <h3>Show the public what was delivered</h3>
          <p>Residents should be able to see the scope, the changes, and the final outcome of a project this significant.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

